______________________________________

IQ] what is the difference between CMD and ENTRYPOINT?
ANS:

  --> CMD instructions are overriden while creating a container, But ENTRYPOINT instructions can't be overrriden while creating a container.
  --> Both the instructions are used to start our container.
_______________________________________________________________________________________________________

IQ] can we keep both CMD and ENTRYPOINT instructions in a Dockerfile?

Ans: Yes, But CMD instructions will not be executed if both are present, CMD instructions will be passed as an argument to the ENTRYPOINT.

  EX: CMD ["ls"]
      ENTRYPOINT ["echo", "Hello"]

    --> It will be executed as below:
       
        /bin/echo Hello ls

       output: Hello ls
in a docker file

CMD
ENTRYPOINT
How it will run?
_______________
ENTRYPOINT defines the fixed command, CMD provides default arguments.
If both are present, CMD is treated as the arguments to ENTRYPOINT.
CMD is overridden at runtime, ENTRYPOINT is not.
_______________________________________________________
Docker supports only one ENTRYPOINT — if multiple ENTRYPOINTs are written, only the last one is applied.
_____________________________________________________________________
what is d/f b/w ARG & ENV?
ARG → Used during image build time only, NOT available in container.

ENV → Used during both build and run time, available inside the running container.

ARG is used for build-time variables and is not available after the image is built.
ENV is used for run-time variables and remains available inside both the image and the running container.





